e=\"Sikkim\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/sikkim.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of Sikkim|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n \n<ref name=\"Tamilnadu\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tamilnadu.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of Tamilnadu|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n \n<ref name=\"Tripura\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tripura.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of Tripura|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n \n<ref name=\"Uttar Pradesh\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of Uttar Pradesh|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n \n<ref name=\"Uttaranchal\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttaranchal.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of Uttaranchal|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n \n<ref name=\"West Bengal\">{{Cite web|url=http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf|title=Central list of OBCs for the state of West Bengal|publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n \n==See also==\n*[[Jangam|Jangam Lingayats]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jogi (Castes)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jogi (Castes)}}\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Brahmin communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Tuluva]]\n[[Category:Other Backward Classes]]\n", "name_user": "106.198.207.214", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jogi_(caste)"}
{"title_page": "Frank Lentini", "text_new": "{{short description|showman}}{{Infobox person\n|name        = Frank Lentini\n|image       = Frank Lentini Zusatzfu\u00df.jpg\n|caption     = Photograph of Lentini as a child.\n|birth_name  = Francesco A. Lentini\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1889|05|18}}<ref name=\"official\">{{official website|http://www.franklentini.it/english-version.html}}.</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Rosolini]], Italy\n|death_date  = {{death date|1966|09|21}} (aged 77)<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|death_place = [[Jackson, Tennessee]], US<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|height      = {{convert|169|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Theresa Murray|1907|1935}}<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|children    =Josephine, Ned, Francis Jr and James<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|partner     = Helen Shupe (1935&ndash;1966)<ref name=\"official\"/>\n}}\n'''Francesco \"Frank\" Lentini<ref name=\"official\" />''' (May 18, 1889 \u2212 September 21, 1966) was an [[Italian-American]] sideshow performer who toured with numerous circuses. Born with a [[parasitic twin]], Lentini had three legs.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nLentini was born on 9 Gintoli Street, [[Rosolini]], [[Sicily]], on May 18, 1889, to farmers Natale and Giovanna Falco. Delivered by midwife Maria Alberino, he was the fifth of 12 children (seven sisters and five brothers) in his family. Disgraced initially, his parents gave him into the care of the wife of uncle Corrido Falco.<ref name=\"official\" /> At four months old he was sent to be examined by a specialist in Naples. By age 5 he was playing with other children and was able to straighten his third leg but not walk.<ref name=\"official\" /> He became known for having three legs, four feet, and two sets of genitals.<ref name=Trivia>{{cite book |last1=Wallechinsky |first1=David |last2=Wallace |first2=Irving |authorlink1=David Wallechinsky |authorlink2=Irving Wallace |title=[[The People's Almanac]] |year=1975 |chapter=Biography of Three-Legged Wonder Franceso A. Lentini Part 1 |chapterurl=http://www.trivia-library.com/b/biography-of-three-legged-wonder-francesco-a-lentini-part-1.htm |via=trivia-library.com |accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLentini was born with a [[parasitic twin]]. The twin was attached to his body at the base of his spine and consisted of a pelvis bone, a rudimentary set of male genitalia, and a full-sized leg extending from the right side of his hip, with a small foot protruding from its knee.\n\n===Sideshow career===\nHe was exhibited in numerous cities including (from 1897) London.  When he was eight, Mantano, a man who ran a traveling puppet show, brought him to Middleton and Lentini's family moved to the [[United States]]. Lentini then entered the sideshow business as ''The Great Lentini'', joining the [[Ringling Brothers Circus]]. He gained US citizenship at the age of 30. His career spanned over forty years and he worked with every major circus and sideshow including [[Barnum and Bailey]] and [[Buffalo Bill]]'s Wild West Show. Lentini was so respected among his peers that he was often called \"The King\".\n\nIn his youth, Lentini used his third leg to kick a [[soccer|football]] across the stage\u2014hence his show name the ''Three-Legged Football Player''. By the time he was six, Lentini's normal legs were slightly different in length:  one was 39 inches and the other 38 inches.  The third leg was only 36 inches and the foot on it was [[club foot|clubbed]].<ref name=Trivia/> As an adult, his primary legs were also two different lengths while his extra leg was several inches shorter. He complained that, even with three legs, he still did not have a pair. In 1907<ref name=\"official\"/> he married Theresa Murray, three years younger than he, and they had four children: Giuseppina (Josephine), Natale (Ned), Francesco (Frank) Junior, and Giacomo (James).<ref name=\"Barresi\">{{cite news |last=Barresi |first=Mario |url=http://www.ragusanews.com/articolo/17157/l-uomo-di-rosolini-che-aveva-tre-gambe-e-due-paia-di-organi-genitali |title=L'uomo di Rosolini che aveva tre gambe. E due paia di organi genitali |work=ragusanews |date=August 29, 2010 |accessdate=September 27, 2012 |language=it |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030537/http://www.ragusanews.com/articolo/17157/l-uomo-di-rosolini-che-aveva-tre-gambe-e-due-paia-di-organi-genitali |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When Frank and Theresa separated around 1935 he began a new life with Helen Shupe, with whom he lived until his death.<ref name=\"official\"/> Lentini died of [[lung failure]] in [[Jackson, Tennessee]], on September 21, 1966, at the age of 77.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nLentini is related to strongman/filmmaker Christopher Annino. Jonathan Redavid portrayed him in the 2017 film ''[[The Greatest Showman]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.jonathanredavid.com/post_news/jonathan-redavid-is-the-3-legged-man-frank-lentini-in-the-new-film-musical-colossal-the-greatest-showman/ |title=Jonathan Redavid is The 3 Legged man Frank Lentini in \"The Greatest Showman\" |date=August 13, 2017 |access-date=February 4, 2018 |last=Leibovitz |first=Annie |author-link=Annie Leibovitz |journal=Jonathan Redavid}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Frank Lentini}}\n*James G. Mundie, [http://www.missioncreep.com/mundie/gallery/gallery11.htm \"The Life History of Francesco A. Lentini, Three-legged Wonder\" pitchbook pamphlet] (with photos)\n*J. Tithonus Pednaud, [http://thehumanmarvels.com/?p=63 Francesco Lentini \u2013 The Three-Legged Man]\n*{{Find a Grave|75952355}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lentini, Frank}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sicilian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Sideshow performers]]\n[[Category:People with parasitic twins]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Italy]]\n[[Category:People with supernumerary body parts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|showman}}{{Infobox person\n|name        = Frank Lentini\n|image       = Frank Lentini Zusatzfu\u00df.jpg\n|caption     = Photograph of Lentini as a child.\n|birth_name  = Francesco A. Lentini\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1889|05|18}}<ref name=\"official\">{{official website|http://www.franklentini.it/english-version.html}}.</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Rosolini]], Italy\n|death_date  = {{death date|1966|09|21}} (aged 77)<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|death_place = [[Jackson,  Tennessee]], US<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|height      = {{convert|169|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Theresa Murray|1907|1935}}<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|children    =Josephine, Ned, Francis Jr and James<ref name=\"official\"/>\n|partner     = Helen Shupe (1935&ndash;1966)<ref name=\"official\"/>\n}}\n'''Francesco \"Frank\" Lentini<ref name=\"official\" />''' (May 18, 1889 \u2212 September 21, 1966) was an [[Italian-American]] sideshow performer who toured with numerous circuses. Born with a [[parasitic twin]], Lentini had three legs.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nLentini was born on 9 Gintoli Street, [[Rosolini]], [[Sicily]], on May 18, 1889, to farmers Natale and Giovanna Falco. Delivered by midwife Maria Alberino, he was the fifth of 12 children (seven sisters and five brothers) in his family. Disgraced initially, his parents gave him into the care of the wife of uncle Corrido Falco.<ref name=\"official\" /> At four months old he was sent to be examined by a specialist in Naples. By age 5 he was playing with other children and was able to straighten his third leg but not walk.<ref name=\"official\" /> He became known for having three legs, four feet, and two sets of genitals.<ref name=Trivia>{{cite book |last1=Wallechinsky |first1=David |last2=Wallace |first2=Irving |authorlink1=David Wallechinsky |authorlink2=Irving Wallace |title=[[The People's Almanac]] |year=1975 |chapter=Biography of Three-Legged Wonder Franceso A. Lentini Part 1 |chapterurl=http://www.trivia-library.com/b/biography-of-three-legged-wonder-francesco-a-lentini-part-1.htm |via=trivia-library.com |accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLentini was born with a [[parasitic twin]]. The twin was attached to his body at the base of his spine and consisted of a pelvis bone, a rudimentary set of male genitalia, and a full-sized leg extending from the right side of his hip, with a small foot protruding from its knee.\n\n===Sideshow career===\nHe was exhibited in numerous cities including (from 1897) London.  When he was eight, Mantano, a man who ran a traveling puppet show, brought him to Middleton and Lentini's family moved to the [[United States]]. Lentini then entered the sideshow business as ''The Great Lentini'', joining the [[Ringling Brothers Circus]]. He gained US citizenship at the age of 30. His career spanned over forty years and he worked with every major circus and sideshow including [[Barnum and Bailey]] and [[Buffalo Bill]]'s Wild West Show. Lentini was so respected among his peers that he was often called \"The King\".\n\nIn his youth, Lentini used his third leg to kick a [[soccer|football]] across the stage -- hence his show name the ''Three-Legged Football Player''. By the time he was six, Lentini's normal legs were slightly different in length:  one was 39 inches and the other 38 inches.  The third leg was only 36 inches and the foot on it was [[club foot|clubbed]].<ref name=Trivia/> As an adult, his primary legs were also two different lengths while his extra leg was several inches shorter. He complained that, even with three legs, he still did not have a pair. In 1907<ref name=\"official\"/> he married Theresa Murray, three years younger than he, and they had four children: Giuseppina (Josephine), Natale (Ned), Francesco (Frank) Junior, and Giacomo (James).<ref name=\"Barresi\">{{cite news |last=Barresi |first=Mario |url=http://www.ragusanews.com/articolo/17157/l-uomo-di-rosolini-che-aveva-tre-gambe-e-due-paia-di-organi-genitali |title=L'uomo di Rosolini che aveva tre gambe. E due paia di organi genitali |work=ragusanews |date=August 29, 2010 |accessdate=September 27, 2012 |language=it |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030537/http://www.ragusanews.com/articolo/17157/l-uomo-di-rosolini-che-aveva-tre-gambe-e-due-paia-di-organi-genitali |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When Frank and Theresa separated around 1935 he began a new life with Helen Shupe, with whom he lived until his death.<ref name=\"official\"/> Lentini died of [[lung failure]] in [[Jackson, Tenneesee]], on September 21, 1966, at the age of 77.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nLentini is related to strongman/filmmaker Christopher Annino. Jonathan Redavid portrayed him in the 2017 film ''[[The Greatest Showman]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.jonathanredavid.com/post_news/jonathan-redavid-is-the-3-legged-man-frank-lentini-in-the-new-film-musical-colossal-the-greatest-showman/ |title=Jonathan Redavid is The 3 Legged man Frank Lentini in \"The Greatest Showman\" |date=August 13, 2017 |access-date=February 4, 2018 |last=Leibovitz |first=Annie |author-link=Annie Leibovitz |journal=Jonathan Redavid}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Frank Lentini}}\n*James G. Mundie, [http://www.missioncreep.com/mundie/gallery/gallery11.htm \"The Life History of Francesco A. Lentini, Three-legged Wonder\" pitchbook pamphlet] (with photos)\n*J. Tithonus Pednaud, [http://thehumanmarvels.com/?p=63 Francesco Lentini \u2013 The Three-Legged Man]\n*{{Find a Grave|75952355}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lentini, Frank}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sicilian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Sideshow performers]]\n[[Category:People with parasitic twins]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Italy]]\n[[Category:People with supernumerary body parts]]